Here's an example of an updated `BaseRepository` class in C# that supports finding by a dynamic field. We'll use the `Expression<Func<T, object>> **BaseRepository with Dynamic Field Finder**

Here's an updated `BaseRepository` class that allows finding entities by a dynamic field. We'll use a generic `IQueryable` interface and a `Func` delegate to achieve this.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Linq;
using System.Linq.Expressions;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

public abstract class BaseRepository<T> : IBaseRepository<T> where T : class
{
    protected readonly DbContext _context;

    protected BaseRepository(DbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    public virtual IQueryable<T> GetAll()
    {
        return _context.Set<T>().AsNoTracking();
    }

    public virtual IQueryable<T> FindByDynamicField(string fieldName, object value)
    {
        var parameter = Expression.Parameter(typeof(T), "x");
        var propertyAccess = Expression.Property(parameter, fieldName);
        var constant = Expression.Constant(value);
        var body = Expression.Equal(propertyAccess, constant);
        var lambda = Expression.Lambda<Func<T, bool>>(body, parameter);

        return _context.Set<T>().Where(lambda);
    }

    // Other methods...
}
```

In the `FindByDynamicField` method, we're using the `Expression` class to dynamically create a lambda expression that represents the condition

